Turkey’s Diplomatic Horizons Spread
Long before Turkey began its efforts to join the European Union, European powers longed to penetrate deep into Turkey's entanglement.
On the eastern bank of the Bosporus, perhaps only twenty steps in Asia, one of the best monuments to this failed imperial ambition stands.
The Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Con in the Neo-Renaissance style.
Well, that's what the tourist guide will tell you.
The building sits at the end of platforms with a tower on every corner of the façade, looking to the undistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone's dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once you get inside the vault, you can no longer have any doubt about the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gate the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German Consortium Anatoli-Bagada Corporation.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to implement its ambitions to take over the Middle East through this railway, which was supposed to lead to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond the territory that is Saudi Arabia today.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their dorms were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
Relative isolation from surrounding areas, created by the frozen Cold War border, is gone.
British and colonial forces advanced from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And bad news came for Hydarpasha Station, too.
In 1917, an explosion of an ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, they have been crumbling and history has been circling it.
But today, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the widening horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling party Justice and Development - AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from surrounding areas, created by the frozen Cold War border, is gone.
A new policy is now in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is remarkable that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iraq and Iran, and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I took the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet one of the leading experts of the AKP on foreign policy, the Turkish MEP Suat Kinikloglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a squirming ride on the tracks that reminded the old-world rhythms of the well-known documentary Night Post, I arrived at the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state, which wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a shift in the paradigm of the Turkish consensus.
In the west, she aroused suspicion, especially in Washington.
The cab brought me to the main tent of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, deliberately built in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and power stores, where middle managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to do early morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a center-right politician from almost any other European political party.
The jacket, the tie, I'm sure he had Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey to its immediate surroundings.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its entanglement.
Today they must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
It had to do both.
"But there will certainly come a time," I asked, "when may Turkey have to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "didn't want such a decision to take place."
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to here said almost by heart: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea are as good for Europe and the United States as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, ride these tracks east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of the two German masters Herr Ritter and Herr Con who watched this building built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that European ambitions in the Middle East can now, for the most part, be in Turkish hands.
And while I was waiting at the port for the ferry back through Bosporus, I remembered that in those days, Turkey was called "a sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
