"The Bee Car" prevents collisions
This time, Nissan was inspired in nature, specifically in bees, to develop technologies to protect against accidents.
This Japanese company created a robot that takes the role of flying bees, thus preventing collisions.
This is Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Centre for Technical Progress Nissan Motor Co. robot developed in cooperation with the Centre for Progress in Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doie, CEO of public relations for technology, research and brand development, BR23C is presented as an extension of four zones of the Nissan security shield.
The robot has the task of strengthening the ability to prevent collisions in vehicles of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to the Nissan security shield.
However, the most important are the composite bee’s eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual function, engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles that are located up to two meters in a radius of 180 degrees before the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment the obstacle is detected, the robot mimics bee movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent collisions.
The biggest difference to any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are absolutely instinctive.
If that were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction by which it is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as with bees.
So in addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent collision.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and to follow these data.
It does not require retention of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, which allows it to function without interruption with only two dozen kB memory.
It may surprise you, but in memory, we're not talking about gigs or megas."
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of precipitation, a technology where Nissan predicts use for serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination and avoid obstacles along the way.
