The Egyptian commando took the attack of the kidnappers of 11 tourists and their eight - member escorts who were captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who were held captive in the desert for ten days, were alive on Monday and safely transported to the Egyptian capital.
An Egyptian commando liberated them in Chad during the morning.
Hostages arrived around 3:30, apparently in good shape, on board a special plane to the military base al-Maza, closely adjacent to the Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred without being able to express themselves in the press, on board helicopters to a hospital in Maadi, the peripheral residential district of Cairo, to be subjected to medical examinations.
"They are quite well" and "no ransom was paid to the kidnappers", said Egypt's Minister of Tourism Zohehr Garrana on the runway.
Since its capture on September 19 during the safari in a four-wheel drive at the foot of Mount Uanat, at the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages have been dragged from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown hijackers.
The group includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border manager of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of safari.
A leader in Egypt’s security forces indicated that 30 special forces who approached the site on board two helicopters set off on the run just before dawn.
"There was a shootout, half the kidnappers were killed and the others fled," said this source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He indicated that a total of 150 members of Egyptian special forces from the unit "glitter" were sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini, from Belgrade, where he is now, mentioned the role played by secret agents and the Italian special forces.
"We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the people from our secret services, from special forces," he said without further clarification.
He also denied that the ransom would be paid.
On the eve before the Sudanese army declared that on patrol they intercepted a four-wheel-drive vehicle on which the kidnappers were on board, killing six of them including the Chadian commander and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a group of rebels in Darfur, the movement for the liberation of Sudan - Unity (SLA-U), which immediately rejected the movement.
