Benelux Governments from Fortis State Bank
Benelux states will help Fortis, the Belgian-Dutch bank, which was the first to get into trouble in Europe because of the widespread effect of the US mortgage market crisis, by partial nationalization: three countries will support the money and insurance institution, which also has capital participation in Hungary, with an amount of EUR 11.2 billion.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch Governments, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition, agreed on this.
Fortis is the first in the euro area to be seen as precedents in the context of the international financial market crisis that has been spreading in waves for more than a year.
In the sense of the decision, which was born on Sunday night, all three states buy almost half (49 percent) of the bank’s assets.
With absolute certainty, the bank will sell some of its equity holdings, especially - mainly insurance - activities purchased last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
The shares of Fortis started to fall sharply last week, and by the second half of the week, serious signs of the crisis appeared in the Institute.
But analysts agree that with their 85 thousand employees, the bank is too big to let it go bankrupt.
The company's securities fell by only 12 percent on Friday, to a 14-year minimum.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
Given the current stock prices, the group’s total market capital value is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the company’s leaders, this is unrealistic.
Moreover, the management blames the fall of Fortis’ shares on the overseas market for the $700 billion US package’s acceptance plan.
On Monday, the stock increased slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx, the new CEO, was appointed as head of the bank.
The money institution was also looking for private buyers, but no one has come forward with a more serious offer.
The Belgian Government has previously announced that investors do not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
There has been no panic between bank clients, and branches have not been taken by attack.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also purchased several leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with a candidate based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the fox's coop," quotes Washington Post Richard Dick, the author of a program designed to monitor prescription drugs.
The insurance company shall make premiums and amounts paid in the case of claims dependent on the health of the candidates and, if the risk is assessed as too large, with or without insurance.
In the past, they sent the persons concerned for medical examinations and concluded the contract only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, the customer from the pharmacies will easily find out what drugs the person has bought in the last year and a half, which will draw the program itself out of what kind of disease he suffers and what his condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol lowering drugs, this refers to his virtually uncontrollably high levels of blood fats, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
Several versions of the program are in circulation, some of them determine the risk coefficient at the same time, so there is almost no work left for the insurance company except for paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
Disadvantages include that many medicines can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
These represent a significant risk-enhancing factor from the point of view of commercial insurance companies, whereas the first mentioned difficulties are not.
In order to request and process data, special companies were created that would ask the patient for permission before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so, even though they have not punished them for their negligence so far.
Some companies have recently already been processing the results of laboratory tests, which combine with data on the medicines used, thus providing an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to the data, while controlling their use will become increasingly complex.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give the authorities the power to control businesses specializing in data provision, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: that is why he has developed his program in such a way that the transfer of data is linked to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that the permission in question can hardly be denied, otherwise the insurance companies will not enter into a contract with it.
So the chickens are somewhat dependent on the fox's goodwill after all.
